{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"53f92e22-3c5a-4400-a7e6-0473b86c782e","content":"In modern MSTest (v3+), you can inject `TestContext` via the constructor and use `[TestInitialize]` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (sync init goes here)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous setup work\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test initialization\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        var result = await _service.DoWorkAsync();\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n\n    // Optional async cleanup\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.DisposeAsync();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — use for sync setup and `TestContext` injection (MSTest 3.x+)\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task` return for async setup; runs before each test\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** / **`[ClassCleanup]`** — for one-time class-level setup (must be `static`)\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern still works but constructor injection is now preferred","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3d96fcd6-0f5c-4355-b0e7-f5b0c0920fd9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), constructor injection for `TestContext` is supported, and you can use `[TestInitialize]` for synchronous init and `[TestInitialize]` also supports async (returning `Task`). Let me provide the recommended pattern.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, the recommended approach is:\n1. Constructor injection for `TestContext` (instead of the old property-based approach)\n2. `[TestInitialize]` for per-test setup (supports async)\n3. `[ClassInitialize]` for one-time class setup\n\n\nNow I'll put together a clear example showing how to set this up.","outputTokens":559,"requestId":"E3DB:14659B:1889628:1B688A8:6A05284A"},"id":"950e5576-2e76-4baf-8bd7-345f1aa0f34d","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:41:42.779Z","parentId":"714636f5-4445-4839-bdc9-85e8f3f2c9a5"}
